      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver verified against ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems for structural mechanics. Required gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical verified against NAFEMS standard benchmarks (LE1, LE10, NL1) with errors <0.5%. Additional patch test and cantilever beam verification completed. Achieved gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating QoI change <1% between successive refinements. Required gradation 3 for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh convergence study performed on pedicle screw and vertebral body block. QoI (stiffness, yield force) changed <0.6% between medium and fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation applied; GCI < 0.8% for all QoIs. Final mesh: ~420,000 elements, predominantly C3D8R hexahedral."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence criteria documented; residual tolerances reported. Required gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver used with force residual tolerance 1e-6 and displacement tolerance 1e-8. Energy criterion also monitored. Convergence confirmed for all 11 model instances; no load-step cutbacks exceeded 3 bisections."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with independent review by second analyst. Required gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Full simulation workflow documented in a controlled simulation plan. Independent analyst reviewed boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions. Discrepancies resolved before results were accepted. Cross-laboratory comparison (FDA vs. DePuy Synthes) further mitigates use error risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model physics (continuum mechanics, contact, plasticity) appropriate for compression-bending construct behavior. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic titanium alloy with isotropic hardening plasticity (Ti-6Al-4V, Ramberg-Osgood fit) used for screw and rod. UHMWPE block modeled as elastic-plastic. Frictional contact (mu=0.3) at screw-block interfaces. Model form validated against published literature and confirmed by experimental correlation across 11 constructs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs characterized from test specimens; uncertainty in inputs quantified and propagated through model. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties sourced from coupon tensile testing of same material lot as test constructs (n=5 coupons). UHMWPE block properties from manufacturer data sheet with ±10% uncertainty bounds applied. Geometric dimensions measured via CMM on 3 representative screws. Input uncertainty quantified using a Monte Carlo approach with 500 samples; coefficient of variation on QoIs reported."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sufficient sample size with traceability to production-representative components. N≥10 constructs required for gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. Components sourced from production lot with full dimensional inspection. Sample size provides 80% power to detect 10% difference in stiffness at alpha=0.05. Traceability records maintained for all specimens."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed at a single ASTM F1717 loading configuration (compression-bending at 5° offset). While this is the standard regulatory configuration, additional load cases (e.g., torsion, lateral bending) were not included in this validation activity. Achieved gradation 2 is below the required level 3; this gap is acknowledged as a limitation of the current validation scope and is acceptable given that the COU is specifically limited to F1717 compression-bending prediction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs matched to experimental conditions; differences documented and bounded. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Experimental boundary conditions (actuator displacement rate, fixture geometry, UHMWPE block dimensions) directly replicated in FEA. Measured load-frame compliance subtracted from experimental displacements before comparison. Temperature (ambient, 23±2°C) matched between labs and simulation assumptions. All parameter differences quantified and shown to contribute <2% to QoI uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed and evaluated against pre-specified acceptance threshold. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Validation metric E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 6.1 for all three QoIs. Experimental uncertainty uval derived from inter-laboratory repeatability (ISO 5725). E/uval values: stiffness 0.87, yield force 1.12, force at 40 mm 1.04 — all below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences all below 10% pre-specified bound. Comparison performed blind prior to unblinding experimental data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to clinical decision criteria and regulatory submission requirements. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in FDA guidance for F1717 spinal implant testing. These QoIs directly inform the structural adequacy assessment for 510(k) clearance. Clinical relevance established by linkage to fatigue failure modes documented in post-market surveillance data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation domain overlaps sufficiently with COU domain; applicability argument documented. Required gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on production-equivalent non-cannulated 7.5 mm screws under the identical loading protocol as the COU. Two-laboratory design provides geographic and equipment independence. Applicability argument documented: screw geometry, material lot, loading conditions, and acceptance criteria are identical between validation and intended COU application. No extrapolation beyond validated domain required."
    }
